  "text": "## Rust Macro Expansion to HIR Lowering Chain\n\nThe Rust compiler's macro expansion and HIR lowering process follows a multi-stage pipeline:\n\n### Stage 1: Compilation Pipeline Orchestration\nThe compilation starts in `rustc_interface/src/passes.rs` which sets up the macro expansion configuration and initiates the process by calling `ExtCtxt::monotonic_expander().expand_crate(krate)`.\n\n### Stage 2: Macro Expansion Engine\nThe main expansion logic resides in `rustc_expand/src/expand.rs`. The `MacroExpander` struct orchestrates the entire process:\n\n1. **`expand_crate()`** - Entry point that recursively expands all macro invocations in the crate\n2. **`fully_expand_fragment()`** - Recursively processes AST fragments by collecting macro invocations and replacing them with placeholders, then expanding them\n3. **`expand_invoc()`** - Dispatcher for individual macro invocations, routing to either procedural or declarative macro handlers based on the `SyntaxExtensionKind`\n\n### Stage 3: Procedural Macro Expansion\nProcedural macros are handled in `rustc_expand/src/proc_macro.rs`:\n- `BangProcMacro::expand()` - Takes a token stream input and executes the procedural macro code through the proc-macro bridge\n- `AttrProcMacro::expand_with_safety()` - Handles attribute-like procedural macros\n\nThe proc-macro server in `rustc_expand/src/proc_macro_server.rs` provides the runtime bridge for executing external proc-macro code.\n\n### Stage 4: Declarative Macro Expansion\nDeclarative macros (\"macro by example\") are implemented in `rustc_expand/src/mbe/`:\n\n1. **Pattern Matching** (`macro_parser.rs`):\n   - `TtParser` implements an NFA-based parser that matches macro input against the LHS patterns\n   - Uses epsilon transitions and Kleene star handling to match token sequences\n\n2. **Macro Expansion** (`macro_rules.rs`):\n   - `MacroRulesMacroExpander::expand()` - Entry point for declarative macros\n   - `expand_macro()` - Core expansion function that:\n     - Calls `try_match_macro()` to match input against defined rules\n     - If matched, calls `transcribe()` to transform the matched tokens\n\n3. **Token Stream Transformation** (`transcribe.rs`):\n   - `transcribe()` - Transforms the matched token patterns by:\n     - Substituting matched variables into the RHS\n     - Expanding Kleene repetitions (`*`, `+`, `?`)\n     - Applying proper spacing and delimiter handling\n   - `TranscrCtx` - Context manager that maintains the transcription state and result stack\n\n### Stage 5: Token Stream to AST Conversion\nAfter macro expansion, the resulting token stream is converted to AST:\n\n1. **`MacroExpander::parse_ast_fragment()`** - Creates a parser from the token stream\n2. **`parse_ast_fragment()` function** - Parses tokens into appropriate AST fragment types (Items, Stmts, Exprs, etc.)\n3. **Placeholder Expansion** - Expanded AST is incorporated back into the original AST by replacing placeholder nodes\n\n### Stage 6: AST to HIR Lowering\nOnce all macros are expanded, the AST is lowered to HIR in `rustc_ast_lowering/`:\n\n1. **`lower_to_hir()`** (`lib.rs`) - Entry point that:\n   - Creates an `ItemLowerer` for traversing the expanded AST\n   - Iterates through all definition IDs and lowers each one\n\n2. **Item-Level Lowering** (`item.rs`):\n   - `ItemLowerer` - Walks through AST items and lowers them to HIR\n   - `lower_item()` - Lowers individual items\n   - `lower_node()` - Lowers a specific AST node to HIR\n\n3. **Expression and Pattern Lowering**:\n   - `expr.rs` - Lowers various expression types\n   - `pat.rs` - Lowers pattern types\n   - `block.rs` - Lowers block-level constructs\n\n### Key Data Structures:\n- **Token Stream**: Sequence of tokens produced by macros\n- **AST Fragment**: Expanded AST nodes (Items, Stmts, Exprs, etc.)\n- **HIR**: Final intermediate representation used for type checking and later compilation stages\n- **NamedMatch**: Captured subexpressions during macro pattern matching\n\nThe entire process maintains proper hygiene information (via `SyntaxContext` and expansion IDs) to ensure correct name resolution and proper error reporting throughout the pipeline."
